    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>Judson proves Lagrange's theorem in Ch. 6 after introducing cosets. The proof is combinatorial: cosets partition G into equal-sized pieces, so |G| = [G:H] * |H|. Normal subgroups and quotient groups (which enable the first isomorphism theorem) are a direct extension: a normal subgroup is one where left and right cosets coincide, making the set of cosets itself a group.</p>

